<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="348" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1049]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
In 1982 (p. 792) Wood designated a 
<typeStatus box="[627,725,610,633]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">lectotype</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName authority="sharpi" authorityName="sharpi Blandford" authorityYear="1898" box="[780,964,610,633]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sharpi" subSpecies="sharpi">
<emphasis box="[780,964,610,633]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">X. sharpi sharpi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
citing the specimen from “Paraiso, prob. 
<collectingRegion box="[151,240,645,668]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[151,240,645,668]" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Panama</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
”, explicitly choosing to interpret the 
<typeStatus box="[643,741,645,668]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">lectotype</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authority="Blandford" authorityName="Blandford" authorityYear="1898" box="[867,1052,645,668]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sharpi">
<emphasis box="[867,935,645,668]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">sharpi</emphasis>
Blandford
</taxonomicName>
as 
<collectingRegion box="[1090,1177,645,668]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[1090,1177,645,668]" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Panama</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, despite acknowledging that Blandford (1896: 199) stated that the locality was in 
<collectingRegion box="[786,904,680,703]" country="Guatemala" name="Guatemala" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[786,904,680,703]" name="Guatemala" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, later confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1129,1432,680,703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" refId="ref3877" refString="Selander, R. B. &amp; Vaurie, P. (1962) A gazeteer to accompany the ' Insecta' volumes of the ' Biologia Centrali-Americana'. American Museum Novitates, 2099, 1 - 70." type="journal article">Selander and Vaurie (1962)</bibRefCitation>
. Among other considerations, this renders his arguments on disjunction of the two “subspecies” irrelevant. Subsequent collections in 
<collectingRegion box="[302,382,749,772]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[435,521,749,772]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingRegion box="[535,620,749,772]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[535,620,749,772]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
) have closed the geographical gap between 
<collectingRegion box="[1095,1190,749,772]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
(
<typeStatus box="[1204,1251,749,772]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1974" box="[1377,1427,749,772]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sharpi" subSpecies="lenis">
<emphasis box="[1377,1427,749,772]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">lenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<collectingRegion box="[197,312,784,807]" country="Guatemala" name="Guatemala" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[197,312,784,807]" name="Guatemala" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
(
<typeStatus box="[327,374,784,807]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blandford" authorityYear="1898" box="[499,567,784,807]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sharpi">
<emphasis box="[499,567,784,807]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">sharpi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). A new record from 
<collectingCountry box="[803,907,784,807]" name="Honduras" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Honduras</collectingCountry>
reported below further reduces any geographical disjunction. Some of Wood’s specimens labeled as 
<taxonomicName authority="sharpi" authorityName="sharpi Blandford" authorityYear="1898" box="[708,880,818,841]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sharpi" subSpecies="sharpi">
<emphasis box="[708,880,818,841]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">T. sharpi sharpi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the declivity more shagreened in appearance, but this character is variable in both Mexican and Costa Rican specimens. In none of his publications did Wood make any mention of the specimens cited by Blandford from 
<collectingRegion box="[741,839,888,911]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1049]" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
Minute morphological differences may seem to justify taxonomic recognition when allopatry is involved. However I have examined numerous specimens from the Mexican states of 
<collectingRegion box="[854,934,957,980]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[989,1075,957,980]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
and all specimens in the 
<collectionCode box="[1354,1435,957,980]" country="USA" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/142r-0w94" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">NMNH</collectionCode>
identified as either 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blandford" authorityYear="1898" box="[358,426,992,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sharpi">
<emphasis box="[358,426,992,1015]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">sharpi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1974" box="[463,513,992,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sharpi" subSpecies="lenis">
<emphasis box="[463,513,992,1015]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">lenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In my opinion the minute differences cited by Wood simply do not merit subspecific recognition and I believe that there is a single species found from southeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[994,1075,1026,1049]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[994,1075,1026,1049]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
to 
<collectingRegion box="[1109,1197,1026,1049]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">
<collectingCountry box="[1109,1197,1026,1049]" name="Panama" pageId="3" pageNumber="348">Panama</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
